model_input:
You are an AI assistant equipped with tools to manage system recoveries.

TOOLS:
[
  {
    "name": "select_recovery_point",
    "description": "Selects a recovery point for a given system based on backup ID.",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "system_name": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "The name of the system to recover."
        },
        "backup_id": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "The ID of the chosen backup."
        }
      },
      "required": ["system_name", "backup_id"]
    }
  }
]

CONTEXT FACTS:
Available backups for the 'payment-gateway' system:
- Backup ID: bk-991 | Created: Oct 1 | TTL: 3 days remaining
- Backup ID: bk-992 | Created: Oct 5 | TTL: 12 days remaining
- Backup ID: bk-993 | Created: Oct 10 | TTL: 45 days remaining

USER: We need to run a recovery for the payment-gateway system. Please select the oldest backup available that has a TTL strictly greater than 10 days.

You have access to the following tools:
[
  {
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
      "name": "recovery_selection",
      "description": "Selects a recovery point or backup snapshot for a given resource.",
      "parameters": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "resource_id": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "The ID of the resource to recover."
          },
          "target_date": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "The target date for recovery in YYYY-MM-DD format."
          },
          "ignore_ttl_expired": {
            "type": "boolean",
            "description": "Whether to ignore snapshots that have passed their Time To Live (TTL)."
          }
        },
        "required": [
          "resource_id",
          "target_date",
          "ignore_ttl_expired"
        ]
      }
    }
  }
]

Context:
- Backups have a default TTL (Time To Live) of 30 days.
- Snapshots older than 30 days automatically expire and are purged unless explicitly marked for long-term retention.
- Expired snapshots beyond their TTL cannot be selected for recovery.

User: I need to restore the server 'srv-web-01' using the backup from 2023-11-15. Make sure to ignore any backups that have passed their TTL since those can't be used anyway.

You are an automated system recovery assistant. You have access to the following tool to handle failover operations:

```json
{
  "name": "execute_recovery_selection",
  "description": "Selects and activates a backup node for system recovery.",
  "parameters": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "selected_node_id": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "The identifier of the backup node to activate."
      },
      "ttl_status": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "The verified TTL status of the node (must be 'Active')."
      }
    },
    "required": ["selected_node_id", "ttl_status"]
  }
}
```

Environment Context (TTL Facts):
- Node Backup-A1: TTL = 300 seconds, Time since last heartbeat = 450 seconds. (Status: Expired)
- Node Backup-B2: TTL = 600 seconds, Time since last heartbeat = 120 seconds. (Status: Active)
- Node Backup-C3: TTL = 300 seconds, Time since last heartbeat = 305 seconds. (Status: Expired)

User Request: The primary database just went down. Please review the TTL facts and execute the recovery selection using the available active backup node.

System: You are an automated disaster recovery assistant. You can use tools to perform operations.

Tools:
[
  {
    "name": "run_recovery_selection",
    "description": "Selects a recovery snapshot based on root configuration.",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "recovery_target": {"type": "string"},
        "root_level": {"type": "integer"},
        "apply_ttl_rules": {"type": "boolean"}
      },
      "required": ["recovery_target", "root_level", "apply_ttl_rules"]
    }
  }
]

Context:
Active Pack: recovery_selection
Configuration: root 2

TTL Facts:
- Snapshot Time-To-Live (TTL) is fixed at 30 days.
- Incremental backups have a TTL of 7 days.
- Any recovery selection must strictly adhere to the TTL to avoid attempting retrieval of purged artifacts.

User: Execute a recovery selection for the 'payment_gateway_prod' environment using root level 2. Make sure you apply the TTL rules based on the snapshot retention facts provided.

SYSTEM: You are a cloud reliability engineer AI. You have access to the following tools:

<tools>
[
  {
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
      "name": "perform_recovery_selection",
      "description": "Executes a recovery selection process for a specified system and root cause diagnostic node.",
      "parameters": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "system_id": {"type": "string", "description": "The ID of the impacted system"},
          "root_node": {"type": "integer", "description": "The identified root cause node"},
          "min_ttl_hours": {"type": "integer", "description": "Minimum required Time-To-Live for the selected backup snapshot"}
        },
        "required": ["system_id", "root_node", "min_ttl_hours"]
      }
    }
  }
]
</tools>

ENVIRONMENT CONTEXT & TTL FACTS:
- Active diagnostic session TTL: 3600 seconds.
- Snapshot backup-A1 TTL: 2 hours (expires soon).
- Snapshot backup-B2 TTL: 72 hours.
- DNS propagation cache TTL: 15 minutes.

USER: The main database 'db-cluster-prod' has crashed due to an index corruption error, which we have identified as diagnostic root 4. Please run the recovery selection for root 4. Since the database is massive, the restoration process will take significant time. To ensure the snapshot doesn't expire during the restore, mandate a minimum TTL of 48 hours for the selection.

